.TH GIT-STAGE-BATCH 1 "March 2026" "git-stage-batch @VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
git-stage-batch \- hunk-by-hunk and line-by-line staging for git
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B git-stage-batch
[\fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR...]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B git-stage-batch
provides a workflow for staging changes to git in a structured, reviewable way.
The tool works by finding hunks in your diff, presenting them one at a time,
and letting you include (stage), skip, or discard each hunk.
.PP
State is maintained in \fB.git/git-stage-batch/\fR so you can stop and continue
later, or run git commands between operations.
.SH INTERACTIVE MODE
.B git-stage-batch
can be run in interactive mode for a continuous hunk-by-hunk workflow
similar to
.BR "git add -p" .
.PP
To start interactive mode:
.RS
.B git-stage-batch interactive
.br
.B git-stage-batch -i
.RE
.PP
Interactive mode automatically starts a session, displays the first hunk with
progress information, and presents a menu of actions. After each action,
the next hunk is automatically displayed.
.SS Actions
.TP
.B i, include
Stage the selected hunk and advance to the next.
.TP
.B s, skip
Mark the selected hunk as skipped and advance to the next.
Skipped hunks can be revisited later.
.TP
.B d, discard
Remove the selected hunk from the working tree and advance to the next.
.B WARNING:
This permanently removes changes.
You will be prompted to confirm.
.TP
.B a, again
Clear state and start a fresh pass through previously skipped hunks.
Resets iteration to review all hunks that were marked as skipped.
.TP
.B l, lines
Enter line selection submenu to include, skip, or discard specific lines
within the selected hunk. Displays changed line IDs, prompts for action, then
prompts for line IDs (e.g., 1,3,5-7).
.TP
.B f, file
Enter file operations submenu to include or skip all hunks from the selected
file. Advances to the next file after the operation.
.TP
.B q, quit
Exit interactive mode. If changes were made during the session, prompts
whether to keep them or undo all changes (abort).
.TP
.B !, command
Run an arbitrary shell command in the repository root directory. Prompts
for the command to execute. Uses readline for command history if available.
.TP
.B ?, help
Display help text showing all available commands.
.PP
At any prompt, press
.B Ctrl-C
to cancel the selected operation and return to the main menu.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS Core Operations
.TP
.B start
Find and display the first unprocessed hunk; cache as "selected".
Resets state if a session is already in progress.
.RS
.TP
.B \-U \fIN\fR, \-\-unified=\fIN\fR
Number of context lines in diff output (default: 3).
.RE
.TP
.B show \fR[\fB\-\-porcelain\fR]
Reprint the cached "selected" hunk.
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-file \fR[\fIPATH\fR]
Show all changes from one file. Without PATH, uses the selected hunk's file.
.TP
.B \-\-files \fIPATTERN\fR...
Show files matched by Git-style patterns.
Patterns use Git's ignore matcher semantics, including ordered \fB!\fR exclusions.
When multiple files match, prints a navigational file list and does not leave
a hidden selected file for later bare actions.
.TP
.B \-\-page \fIPAGES\fR, \-\-pages \fIPAGES\fR
Show one or more file-review pages, such as \fB2\fR, \fB3-4\fR, or
\fBall\fR. Requires \fB\-\-file\fR, or \fB\-\-files\fR resolving to exactly
one file. Cannot be combined with \fB\-\-line\fR or \fB\-\-porcelain\fR.
.TP
.B \-\-porcelain
Exit silently with status code only (0 if hunk exists, 1 if no hunk).
Useful for scripts checking hunk availability without output.
.RE
.TP
.B include
Stage the cached hunk (entire hunk) to the index; advance to next.
.TP
.B skip
Mark the cached hunk as skipped; advance to next.
Skipped hunks can be revisited with
.BR again .
.TP
.B git-stage-batch
When a session is active, running
.B git-stage-batch
with no command shows the selected hunk.
.TP
.B discard
Reverse-apply the cached hunk to the working tree; advance to next.
.B WARNING:
This permanently removes changes from your working tree.
.TP
.B status \fR[\fB\-\-porcelain\fR]
Show session progress and remaining hunks.
Displays iteration number, selected hunk location, progress metrics
(included/skipped/discarded/remaining counts), and a list of skipped hunks.
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-porcelain
Output in machine-readable JSON format for script integration.
The JSON includes: session (iteration and in_progress flag), selected
(selected hunk location or null), progress (counts), and skipped_hunks (array).
.RE
.SS Session Management
.TP
.B again
Clear the blocklist and restart iteration through all hunks.
Useful for making another pass after committing some changes.
.TP
.B stop
End the selected session and remove all state.
.TP
.B abort
Undo all changes made during the session, including commits and discards.
This resets HEAD to where you started, restores your original working tree,
restores batch state (drops created batches, restores dropped/mutated batches),
and removes session state.
.B WARNING:
This will undo any commits made during the session.
.SS Undo and Redo
.TP
.B undo \fR[\fB\-\-force\fR]
Undo the most recent undoable session operation. Restores the repository
state to the point before that operation (index, worktree, session files,
batch refs). Refuses by default if the current state has changed since the
checkpoint.
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-force
Overwrite changes made after the undo checkpoint.
.RE
.TP
.B redo \fR[\fB\-\-force\fR]
Redo the most recently undone session operation. Restores the state that
was in effect before the undo. Multiple undo/redo cycles work in standard
editor order. A new undoable operation after undo clears the redo stack.
Refuses by default if the current state has changed since the undo.
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-force
Overwrite changes made after the undo.
.RE
.SS File-Level Operations
.TP
.B include \-\-file
Stage all hunks from the selected file.
Advances to the next file after staging all hunks.
.TP
.B include \-\-files \fIPATTERN\fR...
Stage all hunks from files matched by Git-style patterns.
.TP
.B skip \-\-file \fR[\fIPATH\fR]
Skip all hunks from a file.
If PATH is omitted, uses the selected hunk's file.
All hunks from the file are marked as skipped and can be revisited with
.BR again .
.TP
.B skip \-\-files \fIPATTERN\fR...
Skip all hunks from files matched by Git-style patterns.
.TP
.B discard \-\-file
Discard the entire selected file from the working tree.
.B WARNING:
This permanently removes the entire file from your working tree.
.TP
.B discard \-\-files \fIPATTERN\fR...
Discard all matched files from the working tree as complete units.
.SS Line-Level Operations
.TP
.B include \-\-line \fILINE_IDS\fR
Stage only specific lines from the selected hunk.
Lines are displayed with IDs in brackets (e.g., [#1], [#2]).
LINE_IDS syntax: single (1), multiple (1,3,5), range (5-7), or combined (1,3,5-7).
For clear one-to-one replacement regions, selecting the matching deleted and
added lines stages that semantic replacement row; if no clear semantic row can
be determined, regular line-level staging is used.
After processing, the hunk is recalculated to show remaining changes.
.TP
.B skip \-\-line \fILINE_IDS\fR
Mark specific lines as skipped without staging them.
Useful when you want to defer certain changes to a later commit.
.TP
.B discard \-\-line \fILINE_IDS\fR
Remove specific lines from the working tree.
.B WARNING:
This permanently removes the specified lines from your working tree.
Allows surgical removal of debug code or unwanted modifications.
.TP
.B include \-\-line \fILINE_IDS\fR \-\-as \fITEXT\fR
Stage replacement text for the selected changed region.
When TEXT includes exact unchanged lines overlapping the preserved file
context immediately before or after the selected span, those edge-overlap
lines are stripped by default.
Replacement selections must form one contiguous displayed line-ID range.
File-scoped views may span omitted gap markers when the selected IDs remain
contiguous, but disjoint ranges still require separate commands.
.TP
.B include \-\-line \fILINE_IDS\fR \-\-as \fITEXT\fR \-\-no\-edge\-overlap
Do not strip unchanged edge-overlap lines from replacement text.
.TP
.B include \-\-file \fIPATH\fR \-\-as \fITEXT\fR
Stage TEXT as the full index content for the selected file-scoped path while
leaving the working tree unchanged.
.TP
.B discard \-\-file \fIPATH\fR \-\-as \fITEXT\fR
Replace the working-tree content for the selected file-scoped path with TEXT
without staging it.
.TP
.B discard \-\-to \fIBATCH\fR \-\-line \fILINE_IDS\fR \-\-as \fITEXT\fR
Save replacement text to a batch and discard the original selected lines
from the working tree.
When TEXT includes exact unchanged lines overlapping the preserved file
context immediately before or after the selected span, those edge-overlap
lines are stripped by default.
Replacement selections must form one contiguous displayed line-ID range.
File-scoped views may span omitted gap markers when the selected IDs remain
contiguous, but disjoint ranges still require separate commands.
.TP
.B discard \-\-to \fIBATCH\fR \-\-line \fILINE_IDS\fR \-\-as \fITEXT\fR \-\-no\-edge\-overlap
Do not strip unchanged edge-overlap lines from replacement text.
.SS Permanent File Exclusion
.TP
.B block-file \fR[\fIPATH\fR]
Permanently exclude a file from all future sessions.
Adds the file to .gitignore, marks it as blocked in session state,
and skips all its hunks automatically.
When run without a selected hunk, you can specify the file path.
.TP
.B unblock-file \fIPATH\fR
Remove a file from the blocked list.
Removes the file from .gitignore and the blocked files list,
allowing its hunks to be processed again.
.SS Fixup Suggestions
.TP
.B suggest-fixup \fR[\fIOPTIONS\fR] [\fIBOUNDARY\fR]
Suggest which commit the selected hunk should be fixed up to.
Finds commits that previously modified the lines in the selected hunk
and suggests them as fixup targets. Iteratively shows candidates starting
from most recent, progressing backwards with each invocation.
Uses git log -L to find commits that touched the affected lines.
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-line \fILINE_IDS\fR
Suggest fixup target for specific lines only.
Useful when a hunk contains changes to multiple unrelated areas.
.TP
.B \-\-reset
Start over from the most recent candidate.
.TP
.B \-\-abort
Clear state and exit without showing candidates.
.TP
.B \-\-last
Re-show the last candidate without advancing.
.TP
.B \-\-porcelain
Output in machine-readable JSON format for script integration.
The JSON includes: candidate (hash, full_hash, subject, author, date,
relative_date), iteration number, and boundary.
.RE
.SS Assistant Assets
.TP
.B install-assets [\fBclaude-agents\fR|\fBclaude-skills\fR|\fBcodex-skills\fR] \fR[\fB\-\-filter\fR \fIPATTERN\fR...] [\fB\-\-force\fR]
Install bundled assistant assets into the current repository.
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\fBclaude-agents\fR installs into \fB.claude/agents/\fR
.IP \(bu 2
\fBclaude-skills\fR installs into \fB.claude/skills/\fR
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
required bundled Claude agents for those skills are installed too
.RE
.IP \(bu 2
\fBcodex-skills\fR installs into \fB.agents/skills/\fR
.TP
.B GROUP
Optionally restrict installation to one bundled asset group.
.TP
.B \-\-filter \fIPATTERN\fR...
Install only bundled assets whose entry names match one or more
gitignore-style patterns. When omitted, all bundled assets from the selected
group are installed, or all bundled assets from every group if no group is
provided.
.TP
.B \-\-force
Overwrite an existing installed skill directory.
.PP
Bundled assistant assets currently include the Claude agent
\fBcommit-message-drafter\fR plus the Claude skills
\fBcommit-staged-changes\fR and \fBcommit-unstaged-changes\fR, and the Codex
skills \fBcommit-staged-changes\fR and \fBcommit-unstaged-changes\fR.
.PP
Installing \fBcodex-skills\fR also writes the shared internal drafter brief at
\fB.agents/internal/commit-message-drafter.md\fR.
.RE
.SH ADVANCED FEATURES
.SS Batch Operations
Batches are named collections of accumulated changes that can be staged or
discarded later as a unit. This is a power-user feature for complex workflows
involving deferred decisions across multiple files or staging passes.
.PP
Most users will not need batches. They are useful when you want to:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Accumulate related changes across multiple hunks for review together
.IP \(bu 2
Defer changes without losing them while you work on other commits
.IP \(bu 2
Group changes by type (e.g., debugging, refactoring) for separate handling
.RE
.PP
Batches are stored as git commits under refs/git-stage-batch/batches/<name>
and persist across sessions until explicitly dropped. Legacy batches under
refs/batches/<name> are read as migration inputs and removed after the batch
is written in the Git-backed namespace.
.TP
.B new \fIBATCH_NAME\fR [\fB\-\-note\fR \fINOTE\fR]
Create a new named batch for accumulating changes.
.TP
.B list
List all existing batches with their descriptions.
.TP
.B drop \fIBATCH_NAME\fR
Delete a batch and remove its git ref.
.TP
.B annotate \fIBATCH_NAME\fR \fINOTE\fR
Add or update the description for a batch.
.PP
The following commands accept \fB\-\-from\fR flags to work with batches:
.TP
.B show \-\-from \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR | \fB\-\-file\fR [\fIPATH\fR] | \fB\-\-files\fR \fIPATTERN\fR...]
Show the accumulated changes stored in a batch.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR to filter display to specific line IDs.
Use \fB\-\-file\fR or \fB\-\-files\fR to limit display to specific batch files.
.TP
.B include \-\-from \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR | \fB\-\-file\fR [\fIPATH\fR] | \fB\-\-files\fR \fIPATTERN\fR...]
Stage the changes from a batch to the index. Fails if the batch's changes
cannot be applied cleanly to the selected state.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR to stage only specific lines from the batch.
Use \fB\-\-file\fR to apply one file from the batch.
Use \fB\-\-files\fR to apply all batch files matched by Git-style patterns.
.TP
.B discard \-\-from \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR | \fB\-\-file\fR [\fIPATH\fR] | \fB\-\-files\fR \fIPATTERN\fR...]
Remove batch changes from the working tree. Fails if the batch's changes
cannot be reversed cleanly. Does not delete the batch.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR to discard only specific lines from the batch.
Use \fB\-\-file\fR to reverse one file from the batch.
Use \fB\-\-files\fR to reverse all batch files matched by Git-style patterns.
.TP
.B apply \-\-from \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR | \fB\-\-file\fR [\fIPATH\fR] | \fB\-\-files\fR \fIPATTERN\fR...]
Apply batch changes to the working tree without staging them.
This adds the batch's changes to your working tree while keeping the index clean.
Fails if the batch's changes cannot be applied cleanly.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR to apply only specific lines from the batch.
Use \fB\-\-file\fR to apply one file from the batch.
Use \fB\-\-files\fR to apply all batch files matched by Git-style patterns.
.TP
.B reset \-\-from \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-to\fR \fIDEST_BATCH\fR] [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR | \fB\-\-file\fR [\fIPATH\fR] | \fB\-\-files\fR \fIPATTERN\fR...]
Remove claims from a batch without changing the working tree.
Use \fB\-\-file\fR with a path to reset only that file from the batch.
Use \fB\-\-files\fR to reset all matched batch files.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR with \fB\-\-file\fR to reset specific line claims from a file.
Use \fB\-\-to\fR to move the reset claims into another batch before removing
them from the source batch.
.PP
The following command uses both \fB\-\-from\fR and \fB\-\-to\fR for batch transformation:
.TP
.B sift \-\-from \fISOURCE_BATCH\fR \-\-to \fIDEST_BATCH\fR
Reconcile a batch against the current tip by removing portions whose effect
is already present in the current working tree state, writing the remainder
to the destination batch.
.RS
.PP
After ad hoc history surgery, some parts of a batch may already have landed
in history while other parts are still unapplied.
.B sift
removes the already-present portions and writes the remaining unapplied
portion to the destination batch.
.PP
Both \fB\-\-from\fR and \fB\-\-to\fR are required.
If \fB\-\-to\fR equals \fB\-\-from\fR, performs an in-place sift.
If \fB\-\-to\fR differs from \fB\-\-from\fR, creates a new destination batch
(which must not already exist) and preserves the source batch unchanged.
.PP
This command does not modify the working tree or staging area.
It only transforms batch ownership to reflect what is still needed.
.PP
Example:
.RS
.nf
# Sift to a new batch
git-stage-batch sift \-\-from feature-cleanups \-\-to feature-cleanups-pruned

# In-place sift
git-stage-batch sift \-\-from feature-cleanups \-\-to feature-cleanups
.fi
.RE
.RE
.PP
The following commands accept \fB\-\-to\fR flags to save changes to batches:
.TP
.B include \-\-to \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR | \fB\-\-file\fR [\fIPATH\fR] | \fB\-\-files\fR \fIPATTERN\fR...]
Save the selected hunk to a batch instead of just skipping it.
Auto-creates the batch if it doesn't exist.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR to save only specific lines to the batch.
Use \fB\-\-file\fR to save one file to the batch.
Use \fB\-\-files\fR to save all matched files to the batch.
.TP
.B discard \-\-to \fIBATCH\fR [\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR | \fB\-\-file\fR [\fIPATH\fR] | \fB\-\-files\fR \fIPATTERN\fR...]
Save the selected hunk to a batch, then discard it from the working tree.
Auto-creates the batch if it doesn't exist.
Useful for saving changes before removing them, allowing later recovery.
Use \fB\-\-line\fR to save and discard only specific lines.
Use \fB\-\-file\fR to save and discard one file.
Use \fB\-\-files\fR to save and discard all matched files.
